          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
          <strong>🇸🇾 Syria's new leader meets the Saudi crown prince on his first trip abroad</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Syria's interim president, Ahmed al-Sharaa, met Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman in Riyadh on his first international visit, signaling a pivot away from Iran from Syria. Al Sharaa <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-02-2025-br1-13-seeks-gulf-investment" target="_blank">seeks Gulf investment</a> and Western support to rebuild Syria's economy. His visit follows a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-br1-14-meeting-with-qatari-emir" target="_blank">meeting with Qatari Emir</a>, highlighting regional reintegration efforts.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Saudi Arabia views distancing Syria from Iran as a strategic win in their proxy dispute. Syria also pushes for sanctions relief, and Riyadh promises diplomatic efforts. While this shift reshapes Middle Eastern alliances, experts express concern that Sharaa's Islamist ties and internal challenges may complicate Syria's stability and the long-term regional alignment with the Gulf.</p>
        </mj-text>
