      <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
          <strong>🇪🇺 EU sleeps on Serbian protests</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Student protests against corruption in Serbia are intensifying, both in Serbia and abroad. However, the EU has been <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-02-2025-br2-15-notably-silent" target="_blank">notably silent</a> in supporting the demonstrators despite Serbia's official EU candidacy since 2012. Protests have been ongoing since the collapse. They are against government corruption and demand transparency in the disaster investigation.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">President Aleksandar Vučić has attempted to suppress protests, while EU officials downplay the issue, citing "steady progress" in Serbia's EU integration. However, the EU's reluctance to criticize Vučić stems from Serbia's strategic geopolitical importance, its role in managing migration, and its valuable resources for European industries. Some other analyses say the EU has to be quiet to avoid appearing to be influencing anything.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

