          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What is a guestworker?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-feb-4-3.png" alt="What is a guestworker?" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            Migrant workers march in protest. Credits: Pop Culture Collaborative
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">A guestworker is a foreign laborer allowed to live and work temporarily in a host country, typically under a government program. These workers are usually brought in to fill labor shortages in agriculture, construction, or hospitality industries. Guestworker programs vary by country and may offer limited rights and benefits. Examples include the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-02-2025-f1-16-bracero-program" target="_blank">Bracero Program</a> in the US and <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-02-2025-f1-17-germany-gastarbeiter" target="_blank">Germany’s Gastarbeiter</a> program.</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Germany and other Western European countries sought workers from other countries in Southern Europe, North Africa, and Turkey to help them rebuild after the Second World War. Many of them stayed, and they have become full citizens and grandchildren in these countries. Some of the integration policies toward these workers were criticized.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Northern and Western Europe still sees a lot of migration within the continent from the Balkans, Eastern, and Southern EU countries in the EU. Many worry about the decrease in population in these countries as many now leave for <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-02-2025-f1-18-educational-and-professional-opportunities" target="_blank">educational and professional opportunities</a> abroad.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Currently, there are <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-02-2025-f1-19-controversial-programs" target="_blank">controversial programs</a> within the Gulf States. These countries attract many guest workers from South and Southeast Asia, and some offer good opportunities. However, for others in more physical labor jobs, countries like the UAE and Qatar have been criticized for the working conditions of migrants. The criticisms were amplified during the 2022 World Cup.
          </p>
        </mj-text> 
      </mj-column>
